s a unique opportunity to shape European perceptions of them while settling conflicting agendas, outshining competing ethnic groups, and carving a place for themselves in the new colonial society. Through archival research and careful visual analysis, Angélica Afanador-Pujol provides a new and fascinating account that situates the manuscript’s images within the colonial conflicts that engulfed the indigenous collaborators. These conflicts ranged from disputes over political posts among indigenous factions to labor and land disputes against Spanish newcomers. Afanador-Pujol explores how these tensions are physically expressed in the manuscript’s production and in its many contradictions between text and images, as well as in numerous emendations to the images. By studying representations of justice, landscape, conquest narratives, and genealogy within the Relación, Afanador-Pujol clearly demonstrates the visual construction of identity, its malleability, and its political possibilities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArtxPolitical aspectszMexicozMichoacán de Ocampo. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszMexicozMichoacán de Ocampo. 0aIllumination of books and manuscriptszMexicozMichoacán de Ocampo. 0aIllumination of books and manuscriptszMexicozMichoacán de Ocampo. 0aIndians of MexicoxEthnic identity. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozMichoacán de OcampoxHistory. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozMichoacán de OcampoxHistory. 7aART / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77138340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477301067423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477301067/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-a